column168: On January 06,2020, at approximately 05:00 a.m. CST, a forklift operated by R+L Carriers(R+L) was operating at the above referenced terminal when the one of the forks made contact with one (1) 55-drum causing a puncture. As a result of the puncture, the drum released approximately 25 gallons of Metallic Ink to the concrete terminal floor. R+L personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted concrete to contain the release. At approximately 05:51 a.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental clbanup on their behalf. Based on the available information the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from TAS Environmental Services(TAS) located in Dallas, Texas to assess the site and initiate corrective actions. TAS arrived and assessed the site. The crew dawned the appropriate personnel protective equipment and deployed additional granular absorbents to the impacted concrete. TAS utilized hand tools to collect the granular absorbents from the impacted concrete and placed the material into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. The crew placed the damaged drum into one(1) 95-gallon over pack drum for transport and disposal. The crew collected the drums and demobilized.

column168: On January 06, 2020, at approximately 02:15 a.m. CST, trailer OA5145 operated by R+L Carriers (R+L) was parked at the above referenced terminal when facility personnel observed a leak coming from the trailer due to a shift load. As a result of the shifted load, a 55-gallon drum released approximately 10 gallons of material to the trailer floor and migrated to the asphalt parking lot. R+L personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted asphalt to contain the release. At approximately 03:08 a.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup on their behalf. Based on the available information the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Environmental Remediation Specialist, (ERS) located in Tulsa, Oklahoma to assess the site and initiate corrective actions. The crew dawned the appropriate person protective equipment and deployed additional granular absorbents to the impacted asphalt. ERS unloaded the trailer, deconstructed the pallets, and removed the damaged drum from the trailer. The crew placed the damaged 55-gallon drum into a 95-gallon drum for transport to the products end destination. The crew- utilized hand tools to collected the spent absorbentsinto one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ERS secured th6 site and demobilized.

On January 06, 2020, at approximately 01:00 a.m. CST, a R+L Carriers(R+L) trailer OE1342 was parked at the above referenced terminal when R+L personnel observed a 330-gallon tote crushed and missing it's cap due to improper stacking. As a result of the improper stacking, the lid of the 330-gallon tote released approximately 10 gallons of sodium hydroxide to the trailer floor. At approximately 03:43 a.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Se,vices, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup on their behalf. Based on the available information the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from TAS Environmental Services (TAS) located in Dallas, Texas to assess the site and initiate corrective actions. The crew dawned the appropriate person protective equipment and began to offload the trailer. TAS wiped down adjacent product and staged it on poly sheeting in the terminal. The crew transferred the remaining sodium hydroxide from the damaged tote to a new tote. The crew placed the new tote on poly sheeting in the terminal. The crew deployed granular absorbents/citric acid to the impacted trailer. The crew collected the spent absorbents/acid into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. TAS collected the damaged tote and the 55-gallon drum and demobilized.

column168: On January 8,2020, at approximately 4:45 am CST, a representative with R+L Carriers observed a damaged pallet containing a punctured 15-gallon container of phosphoric acid on trailer OA2605. As a result, approximately seven(7) gallons of phosphoric acid was released to the trailer floor. At approximately 4:59 am CST, a representative with R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Emergency Remediation Specialist(ERS) to asses and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 8:35 am CST, a crew from ERS arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, ERS personnel noted approximately 7 gallons of phosphoric acid released to the trailer floor. Crews removed the damage container and deployed a nutralizing agent to the impacted area. Once the chemical was neturalized, ERS personnel deployed granular absorbents and worked them in using hand tools. All phosphoric acid impacted material was collected and containerized in three (3) 55-gallon poly drums for transport and disposal. ERS personnel noted no further actions were required on-site and crews demobilized.

A flatbed trailer with a leak pan was loaded with transformers and transformer parts, some of which contained mineral oil and at least one contained PCBs.  The driver was travelling on hwy 174 near Pell City Alabama when he encountered a car that was stopped (or appeared to be stopped) in the middle of the road. the driver of the truck tried to get the driver of the pick up truck's attention but to no avail.  steps to avoid the accident failed and the big truck clipped the smaller truck in the right rear and both vehicles overturned onto the road shoulder.  the trailer attached to the big truck was on its left side overhanging a small but active creek.  an untold amount of mineral oil and 10 gallons of pcb oil leaked into the creek before the truck and trailer could be up-righted.  the total amount of time that the oils dripped into the creek was approximately 2 hours.  A clean-up crew was immediately dispatched and they put out spill booms and other materials for a distance of approximately 4 miles in the creek and two vacuum trucks were brought in the help vacuum off the oils.
column169: For the severity of the damage to the truck and trailer the transformers on the trailer held up well.  small openings in the covers on the transformers opened enough to allow some oil to drip out at a slow rate. The best way to insure that this would not occur in the future would be to insist that the transformers were completely emptied of oil before transporting and allow the oil to be shipped only in fully seal able and leak-proof containers.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON RT 22, HAD A FULL VIEW OF HIGHWAY 3/4 OF A MILE AHEAD. SAW A JEEP GO SIDEWAYS INTO GUIDE RAIL ON HER SIDE OF ROAD. THEN JEEP SHOT ACROSS 3 LANES AND WENT UP BANK ON OUR DRIVERS SIDE OF ROAD. DRIVER STARTED TO FADE TO THE LEFT HOPING THE OTHER VEHICLE WOULD STOP BUT CONTINUED OUT ON ROAD INTO MIDDLE LANE WHERE OUR DRIVER TRIED TO GO AROUND BUT HIT JEEP ON PASSENGER SIDE REAR, DRIVER WAS NOW IN WRONG LANE WITH TRAFFIC HEADING TOWARD HIM HE TURNS TO THE RIGHT TO GET BACK IN HIS OWN LANE LOOKS OUT MIRROR SEE'S REAR TIRES LEAVING ROAD. ROLLS ON DRIVERS SIDE AND SLIDES ON ROAD HITS GUIDE RAIL WITH FRONT OF TRUCK THAT SPINS TRUCK AND COMES TO REST WITH REAR OF TRUCK AGAINST GUIDE RAIL IN HIS LANE.
column169: OTHER DRIVERS NEED TO STAY IN THEIR OWN LANES AND KEEP THEIR VEHICLES UNDER CONTROL.

DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO HIS FIRST DELIVERY HEADING EAST ON HWY 66, WHICH IS A NARRO 2 WAY ROAD. OUR DRIVER SAID THAT THERE WAS ANOTHER COMMERCIAL TRUCK HEADING WEST ON HWY 66 AND HE ATTEMPTED TO MOVE OVER NEAR THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD TO ALLOW FOR CLEARANCE FOR THE 2 TRUCKS TO PASS. OUR DRIVER DROVE TOO FAR OFF THE SHOULDER AND HIT THE DITCH, CAUSED HIS TRUCK TO OVERTURN. THE DRIVER CALLED HIS MANAGER TO INFORM HIM OF THE ACCIDENT AND GET HELP TO THE SCENE. OUR DRIVER INDICATED THAT HE WAS NOT INJURED DURING THIS CALL. EMPLOYEES AND MANAGEMENT HEADED TO THE SCENE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE. I WAS ALSO CALLED AND STARTED HEADING TO THE SCENE AND WAS ABOUT ONE HOUR AWAY. WHEN I ARRIVED, EMPLOYEES HAD ALREADY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE SLOW DRIP OF LEAKING DIESEL FUEL THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANK LIDS. EMPLOYEES ALSO HAD PLACED SORBENT PADS DOWN UNDER THE BUCKET AS A PRECAUTION. WHEN I WAS ON PHONE WITH THE MANAGER AT THE SCENE I THOUGHT I HEARD HIM TALKING WITH FIRST RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED I REALIZED THAT 911 HAD NOT BEEN CALLED SO THAT WAS THE FIRST THING THAT WE DID. THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASE OCCURRED DURING THE HAZMAT CREW PUMPING OUT THE TANK BEFORE THEY WOULD ALLOW US TO UPRIGHT THE TRUCK.
column169: THE MAIN ISSUE IDENTIFIED DURING THE INVESTIGATION WAS THAT THE DRIVER WAS "OFF ROUTE". THE DRIVER SAID HE WAS UNAWARE OF DESIGNATED HAZMAT ROUTES AND HAD BEEN RUNNING THE ROAD FOR MANY YEARS. IF HE WOULD HAVE FOLLOWED THE DESIGNATED ROUTES, HE WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN TRAVELING ON THE NARROW ROAD AND AVOIDED THE SITUATION. ALL DRIVERS WERE TRAINED ON THE DESIGNATED HAZMAT ROUTE MAP FOR OUR AREA IN COLORADO. WE ALSO UTILIZED THE NATIONAL PROPANE GAS ASSOCIATION TRAINING VIDEO TITLED PREVENTING BOBTAIL ROLLOVERS.

On 01/05/2020, at 1944 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parsons Yard discovered UTLX 203409, a residue tank car of Ethyl Acrylate, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-0105-00031). Enviroserve, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor leak from liquid line flange to fittings plate threaded connection. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Mike Busby of SASOL, phone 337-499-1472. Contractor personnel tightened the liquid line valve and wrapped the valve and protective housing in poly sheeting. The leak was secured and the car will be released for transport upon completion of an OTMA. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 283 NARRI: 28

On 01/07/2020, at 1252 hours, an FRA Hazmat Inspector in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard took exception to PROX 633039 as having loose closures. PROX 633039 was a loaded tank car of Isoprene, Stabilized. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia DEP were notified.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found liquid, vapor, and sample line secondary closures less than tool tight, and a vapor release emanating from the vapor line valve due to a partially open valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Ms. Aimee Dose, phone 904-928-8837. Contractor personnel secured all valves and closures, and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 will be completed  Cause Code: 134 NARRI: 40

On 01/09/2020, at 1117 hours, an FRA Hazmat Inspector notified personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard the they discovered NATX 400758, a residue tank car of Propane, leaking from the vapor valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Maryland Department of the Environment were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-0109-00140). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve 1/8 of a turn open and secondary closure improperly secured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Sean Underwood of Poist Gas, phone 443-414-9582. Contractor personnel closed the valve and properly installed the secondary closure plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 134 NARRI: 90

column17: PANHANDLE EXPRESS ENERGY SERVICES LLC DBA SMART CHEMICAL LOGISTICS
column168: ON 1-14-20. LOGISTICS DRIVER MICHAEL GALVEZ WAS DRIVING ON 1-35 IN OKLAHOMA CARRYING 11 TOTES OF HAZMAT. AT APPROXIMATELY 11AM AT MM 205 MICHAEL TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROAD TO REACHED DOWN TO GRAB HIS DRINK. AS MICHAEL LOOKED AWAY HE STRUCK A TRUCK THAT WAS PARKED ON THE SHOULDER. NO INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED AND ONLY MINOR DAMAGE TO BOTH VEHICLES. PIECE OF FLYING DEBRIS CAUSED DAMAGED TO ONE THE TOTES CARRYING JC3600W SCALE INHIBITOR. MICHAEL FOLLOWED EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURE AND CONTACTED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND SMART CHEMICAL'S SAFETY DEPARTMENT. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS USED EQUIPMENT TO LAY THE DAMAGED IBC  ON ITS BACK TO ELIMINATE FURTHER LOSS. THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT FROM GUTHRIE, OK TO TRANSFER OVER THE REMAINING CHEMICAL, COMPLETE THE CLEANUP & DISPOSAL OF LOST MATERIAL AND THE DAMAGED IBC. TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS APPROX. 10 GALLONS. MICHAEL COMPLETED A DOT POST ACCIDENT DRUG AND ALCOHOL TEST LATER THAT EVENING IN ENID, OK.
column169: MICHAEL WAS ISSUED A DISCIPLINARY ACTION NOTICE FOR UNSAFE DRIVING CAUSED BY THE DISTRACTION OF REACHING FOR HIS DRINK. IN ADDITION TO THE DISCIPLINARY ACTION NOTICE, MICHAEL WILL ATTEND OUR SMITH SYSTEM SAFE DRIVING COURSE AND COMPLETE A FUNCTION SPECIFIC LABELING, PLACARDING AND LOAD SECUREMENT REFRESHER COURSE.

column168: Veolia employees loaded 6 x 55 gallon drums of acetone onto the vehicle on 1/7/2020. The drums  were strapped to the side wall of the truck using the e-track strap to secure the load. There were  no leaks reported by the individuals who loaded the drums. The following morning, on 1/8/2020,  the driver drove the trailer to the Veolia 10 day in-transit facility located in San Diego, CA, where it  would be off-loaded for subsequent delivery to the customer. Upon opening the trailer door, Veolia employees noticed liquid material on the floor of the trailer. Further investigation revealed one of  the drums was leaking. The Veolia employees overpacked the leaking drum into a salvage drum  and cleaned up the spill.  After examining the leaking drum, it was discovered that a portion of the  chime showed bare metal and appeared to be abraded from either being dragged or rubbed. The  shipper confirmed that these drums were brand new and there was no other damage aside from  the abrasion. Based on our understanding of the incident, we believe there were multiple factors that caused the spill. The drum may have had a compromised chime from the manufacturer, or the drum was improperly handled which abraded the chime; during transportation, the drum was  vibrating which cracked the chime and caused the release.
column169: Based on the information, the drum should not have leaked due to normal conditions of transportation unless it was already compromised. Veolia will retrain its employees on inspecting drums prior to  shipment, especially regarding chimes and proper handling so that chimes do not become abraded or damaged during the handling process. One thing to note is that the drum did not show any other  damage such as a dent near or around the chime which leads Veolia to believe that this was a  possible manufacturer's defect.

column168: On January 24,2020, facility personnel at the R+L Carriers(R+L) Sanger terminal located at the above-mentioned address discovered leaking cargo inside trailer OA1647 docked at door 105. A large battery containing battery acid, tipped over inside the trailer and released approximately 20 gallons of battery acid to the trailer and leaked to the concrete dock. R+L terminal personnel deployed granular absorbents to the release for containment. At approximately 10:06 p.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup of the site. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat(LSH) to assess and remediate the site. On January 25,2020, LSH personnel arrived and assessed the site. Crews observed battery acid impact to the trailer interior and pavement below the trailer. The cargo was offloaded from the trailer and crews collected impacted absorbents. The impacted surfaces were neutralized and wiped down. The battery which tipped over was re-palletized, wrapped in poly sheeting, and staged at the terminal. All waste was containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. Once the cleanup was complete, crews secured the scene and demobilized.

On January 13, 2020, at approximately 11:40 AM CST, a driver for Landstar System Holdings, Inc.(LSH) was unloading his cargo at the above-referenced location when he observed released residual product to the wood trailer floor. At approximately 12:51 AM CST, a representative for LSH retained Cura Emergency Services(CES) to manage the environmental remediation on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Lonestar Hazmat(LH) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 2:03 PM CST, a crew from LH arrived on site and donned the proper personal protective equipment. The crew completed a site assessment and noted an unknown released liquid onto the wooden trailer floor. LH personnel tested the PH of the liquid and noted a PH of 5-6. After reviewing the bill of Iading, crews believed the characteristics of the unknown liquid resembled that of naphtha. LH personnel deployed granular absorbents to the released product and worked them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one(1) bag. column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: OWNER/OPERATOR: REVERE SMELTING & REFINING CORPORATION  DATE: JANUARY 10, 2020 AT 7:00AM  LOCATION: ROUTE 22 EAST (MILE MARKER 321), WHITEHALL PA  DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON ROUTE 22 WHEN TRAFFIC CAME TO A SUDDEN STOP IN FRONT OF HIM AND HE IMPACTED THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM. THE BRAKING AND IMPACT CAUSED THE BATTERIES TO SHIFT WITH SEVERAL TIPPING OVER IN THE TRAILER. THE TIPPED BATTERIES RESULTED IN THE DILUTE SULFURIC  ACID SPILLING INTO THE TRAILER WITH A SMALL QUANTITY DRIPPING THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR ONTO THE TRAILER TIRES AND ASPHALT BENEATH. LOCAL POLICE, FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO ACID WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT, BUT CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED OF THE IMPERVIOUS SURFACES AND TRAILER INTERIOR. A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE CLEANUP CREW, HIRED BY REVERE SMELTING & REFINING CORPORATION, CLEANED UP THE ACID FROM THE ROADWAY AND TRAILER.
column169: REVERE IS INVESTIGATING THE INCIDENT, BUT HAS REVIEWED SAFE FOLLOWING DISTANCES AND SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES WITH THE DRIVER.

column168: - SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT 1462, A THROUGH FLIGHT ARRIVED FROM CRP AND WAS IN THE BOARDING PROCESS IN HOU WHEN AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE OVERHEAD BIN. - THE CLEANING CREW CALLED AND WAS UNAWARE OF WHAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS AND INADVERTENTLY SPREAD IT FROM THE OVERHEAD BIN TO THE SEATS BELOW AND THE CARPETING. - IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS MERCURY. - BOARDING WAS STOPPED & 30 PASSENGERS AND 5 CREW MEMBERS DEPLANED. - AIRCRAFT N457WN WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND MOVED TO A REMOTE LOCATION. - SWA CONTRACT A 3RD PARTY VENDOR TO COMPLETE TESTING, CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION.  TSOC HAS BEEN PROVIDED WITH UPDATES REPORT # TSA-01-00297-20  NRC REPORT # 1267925 - FAA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AVIATION SAFETY INSPECTOR LUIS "LOU" HERNANDEZ HAS BEEN PROVIDED UPDATES. - PICTURES ARE AVAILABLE.  WE HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE DIME SIZED AMOUNT OF MERCURY THAT WAS DISCOVERED IN THE OVERHEAD BIN.  QUESTIONS 24 & 25 - CONTAINMENT WAS DISCOVERED WITHOUT SOURCE PACKAGING AND CANNOT DETERMINED WHAT FAILED. QUESTIONS 38 & 40 - INCIDENT OCCURRED IN CABIN OVERHEAD BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT & NO WAY TO CONFIRM IF THIS 1ST FIT.  PICTURES ARE AVAILABLE

column168: JUST AFTER EXITING THE COVESTRO PLANT, THE TRAILER FELL OFF OF THE TRACTOR, RESULTING IN A PUNCTURE TO THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY THE KINGPIN WAS NOT  PROPERLY ENGAGED AND THE RELEASE HANDLE WAS NOT LOCKED INTO THE FIFTH WHEEL TO PREVENT SEPARATION BETWEEN THE TRUCK AND THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 3,600 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND MIGRATED INTO A NEARBY CREEK. FIRST RESPONDERS RESPONDED AND DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY AND INTO THE CREEK. column168: FOR THE PAST THREE MONTHS WE HAVE BEEN PUMPING DOWN CINCINNATI-KENTUCKY AIRPORT HYDRANT SYSTEM TO REPLACE VALVES. THE PROCEDURE IS TO HOOK OUR 3 INCH BLACKMEAR PUMP TO THE LOW POINT DRAIN AND A 1 INCH LINE TO THE TOP VENT OF THE PUMP WE ARE PUMPING. THE PUMP IS HOOKED TO THE BOTTOM LOADER OF THE TRAILER AND THE VENT IS RAN INTO THE DOME LID ON TOP. THE PUMP IS STARTED AND THE DRIVER IS ON TOP TO VERIFY THE VENT IS WORKING AND THE PRODUCT IS FLOWING. WE HAVE A SIGHT GLASS ON THE BOTTOM LOADER TO MONITOR THE FUEL.  IT TAKES TWO HOURS TO FILL THE TRAILER. AT 15 MINUTE INTERVALS THE DRIVER GOES BACK UP TOP TO CHECK THE FLOW. AFTER GETTING ON TOP HE REALIZED THE TANK WAS ALMOST FULL SO WE SHUT OFF ALL THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER AND PUMP. THE DRIVER THEN TRIED TO REMOVE THE VENT LINE AND REALIZED THE VENT LINE WAS NOT FLOWING.THE VENT LINE SHUT OFF IS LOCATED IN A VAULT UNDERGROUND WHERE CONFINE SPACE PERSONNEL ARE REQUIRED TO BE.ALL CONFINE SPACE PERSONNEL HAD GONE TO ANOTHER VAULT. WE NOTIFIED THE ENGINEER AND HE DROVE DOWN TO THE VAULT WHERE THE PERSONNEL WERE AT AND HAD THEM GO BACK TO THIS VAULT.DURING THIS TIME (ABOUT 5 MINUTES) WE PUT TWO HALF DRUMS UNDER THE LATTER DRAIN AT THE END OF THE TRAILER BUT ONCE THOSE FILLED UP IS WHEN IT STATED TO OVERFLOW.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE AIRPORT OPERATION. THE AIRPORT ENVIRONMENTAL PERSON ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER THE SIGHT. AN AIRPORT VAC TRUCK ARRIVED AND IMMEDIATELY AND BEGAN VACUUMING AND STARTED THE CLEANUP. WE CLOSED UP THE TRAILER AND ALL OF OUR EQUIPMENT. THEY HAD US LEAVE AND TAKE THE REMAINING FUEL TO THE AIRPORT FUEL FARM.  LATER THAT DAY IT WAS DETERMINED THE FUEL FARM ATTENDANT HAD TURNED ON A VALVE THAT WAS NOT TAGGED AND LOCKED OUT LIKE IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN. WHEN THIS WAS DONE IT RE-ENERGIZED THE LINE WE WERE PUMPING.
column169: THE NEW CHANGES ARE AS FOLLOWS: ENGINEERING, CONFINE SPACE PERSONAL AND JET STAR PERSONEL WILL HAVE TWO WAY RADIOS WHEN ANY PUMPING IS BEING DONE. ALL CONFINE SPACE PERSONEL WILL BE AT THE VAULT AT ALL TIMES WHILE PUMPING. TAGGED AND LOCK OUT PERSONEL WILL RECHECK ALL VALVES BEFORE PUMPING FRO PROPER TAGGED OUT AND LOCKOUT.

column168: Univar Solutions received Railcar GATX5617 and unsealed the dome lid connections to begin offloading the product. The manifold used by Univar Solutions to connect to the railcars was attached to the railcar (via a threaded connection) and a compressed air line was connected to the railcar via a separate connection. The railcar car was pressurized and when the switch was engaged to open the air actuated valve on the manifold to begin the acid flow, the manifold blew off the railcar connection. Note railcar GATX5617 is a top load/unload configured tank car, there are no bottom connections on this railcar. Once the manifold released off the car, the acid was pushed out of the tank car until the air pressure equalized with atmospheric pressure at which time the release ceased. No air, surface water, or ground water was impacted by the acid release to our knowledge.  A small area of soil adjacent to the rail spur of approximately 10-15 feet square was impacted by the release.  Univar Solutions mobilized an emergency response team to the release location and the impacted soil was scraped off using a skid steer excavator to a lined roll-off box which was staged to hold the soils pending profiling for proper disposal. The ground surface under and immediately adjacent to the rails is protected by a series of containment / collections pans.  According to East Penn representatives, these pans are plumbed to an underground stormwater collection and holding tank system.  The majority of the released acid was captured by the pans and drained to their self-contained underground stormwater collection / holding tank system.  The emergency response team pumped out the underground holding tank and collection pipes.  The inspection markings on the side of the railcar indicated this car was on the last year of its inspection / service life. An inspector from the Federal Railroad Administration visited the incident location on January 24, 2020 to observe the railcar. The condition of the threaded offloading connection (which is an integral component of the DOT specifications of the rail tank car) was observed to be suspect as the threads were significantly worn.
column169: As a result of the incident, Univar Solutions reviewed our equipment and documentation. We are evaluating the use of a measuring device (e.g., micrometer) to evaluate the thread condition of the rail car and our manifold before we hook up to the rail car. We have also reviewed the condition of our manifold devices and replaced fittings on two of the manifolds. Lastly, Univar Solutions is evaluating alternative designs and materials of construction for the manifold devices used to connect to the rail cars. In addition, Univar Solutions has purchased a preventative maintenance program from the supplier of the acid transfer trailer to provide third party expert oversight in this process.

On January 26, 2020, at 16:33 hours personnel in the CSXT Owensboro, KY yard reported product leaking from the bottom car PROX 23115, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2020-0126-00050.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched and found the source of the release was due to a faulty bottom outlet valve and an aged gasket which was preventing the bottom outlet valve’s secondary closure cap from containing the release.  MEI was able to install a new gasket in the secondary closure cap which stopped the release.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper’s representative: Mr. Shane Stuntz.  Shell Chemical obtained a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA and the car was delivered to industry for unloading without further product release.
column169: (NAR code: 544 5 What Failed: Bottom Outlet Valve Where Failed: Connection between valve and tank car Why Failed: Mounting flange gasket deteriorated)

column168: On January 8,2020, personnel at the R+L Carriers(R+L) Dallas terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a Leaking container of paint inside a trailer at door 24. As a result of the leak, approximately one-half gallon of UN1263 white paint was released to the trailer interior. At approximately 10:10 a.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup of the site. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from TAS Environmental Services (TAS) to assess and remediate the site. TAS personnel arrived and assessed the site. Crews deployed absorbents pads to recover the release. Remaining paint stains on the trailer were treated with paint thinner and wiped down to remove as much staining as possible. TAS collected all impacted debris and four(4) boxes of impacted/damaged paint cargo. Each box contained two (2) half-gallon buckets of paint for disposal. All waste was containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport from the terminal.

column168: ON JANUARY 23, 2020, O'NEALGAS DRIVER CHADRICK PARKER WAS OPERATING A 2011 FREIGHT LINER BOBTAIL LPG DELIVERY TRUCK. HE WAS EN ROUTE TO HIS FINAL TWO RESIDENTIAL DELIVERIES WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. HE WAS TRAVELING ON BURKE RD. IN RURAL RICHLAND PARISH. HE DIVERTED HIS ATTENTION OFF THE ROADWAY AND LEFT SIDE TIRES DROPPED OFF THE LEFT EDGE OF THE ROAD. HE OVERCORRECTED, STEERING TO THE RIGHT, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO CROSS THE ROAD AND OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. THE VEHICLE STRUCK A TREE OFF ROAD RIGHT, RE-ENTERED THE ROADWAY AND CAME TO REST ON IT'S LEFT SIDE ON THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER, WHO WAS NOT WEARING A SEABELT, WAS EJECTED. AFTER IMPACT. THE CAB OF THE TRUCK CAUGHT FIRE. THE HEAT FROM THE CAB FIRE CAUSED THE TWO RELIEF VALVES ON THE TANK TO OPEN AND RELEASE PROPANE. THE PROPANE IGNITED AND APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS WERE BURNED OFF UNTIL THE RELIEF VALVES RESEALED. THE TANK ITSELF DID NOT SUSTAIN ANY STRUCTURAL DAMAGE AND VALVES WORKED AS DESIGNED. THE DRIVER SUSTAINED MODERATE INJURIES FROM BEING EJECTED FROM TRUCK.  LA STATE POLICE HAZMAT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED: INCIDENT #20-00291 LA STATE POLICE INVESTIGATED TRAFFIC CRASH: REPORT #20200004308 HOLLY RIDGE FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED TO SCENE: REPORT #42025
column169: IN THIS INCIDENT IT WAS OBVIOUSLY THE FAULT OF THE DRIVER FOR BEING INATTENTIVE, DISTRACTED AND NOT WEARING A SEAT BELT. THIS DRIVER WAS TERMINATED AND ADDITIONAL DRIVER TRAINING/EDUCATION INITIATED FOR ALL DRIVERS.

column168: During routine facility operations of staging pallets, a container fell from the pallet resulting in a release of its contents. Upon investigation of the container, it was identified that the materiel was not packaged in accordance with 49 CFR 173.12(b) Exceptions for shipment of waste materials (Lab packs). The outer container did not have a UN specification authorizing its use for shipment of a hazardous material. Further, the inner containers were not packaged with a chemically compatible material as per 49 CFR 173.12(b)(i).  The release was contained to the warehouse floor, with no threat or impact to water ways, soil, environment nor storm drains. The impacted areas were sufficiently cleaned by trained personnel in appropriate personal protective equipment. The containers were sent to their final destination without further incident.
column169: Generator was notified of the release and advised on packaging selection authorized for the hazardous material they intend to ship. Generator was further advised on preparation of material to sustain the rigors of transportation per the hazardous materials regulations. The driver who accepted the material into transportation was retrained on thorough container inspection to include validation of containers UN specification rating for the hazardous material.

column168: On January 27, 2020, at 2114 ET, ERTS was contacted by terminal personnel at ABF Freight in Cohoes, New York regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, (1) 55-gallon poly drum of T-100 Aliphatic Thinner (Alkylamines, liquid, corrosive, UN2735) was damaged, releasing approximately 55 gallons of product on to a 20' by 10' area of the trailer floor and continuing on to a 50' by 10' area of the parking lot.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum, spent absorbents and all other waste debris generated were containerized in (1) 95-gallon and (4) 55-gallons waste drums.  The 95-gallon drum containing the damaged drum was forwarded on to the consignee; the (4) 55-gallon waste drums were taken off site by the contractor for disposal.

column168: A shipment was received at the Lemont Heritage Transport facility on 01/17/2020. On 01/20/2020, three containers from this shipment were offloaded from a trailer, staged on the dock, and being weighed and loaded on a second trailer. One container was moved off the scale and placed on the ground. One minute later, a leak was discovered under this container. Chemists reported event to their supervisor. (1) The container was over-packed, leak was stopped 3-4 minutes after discovery (2) Approximately 1 liter of spillage, containing 4-5% sulfuric acid/water mixture, was neutralized with lime and cleaned up promptly by onsite personnel. Clean up was complete within 15 minutes. Upon investigation, it was determined the container bottom had a small 2-3" crack on the bottom seam of plastic drum. Cause may have been from handling, drum integrity, weather, or combination.
column169: With personnel, emphasize importance of handling containers with mechanical devices. Containers need to be handled with contents, weight, type of container, temperature/weather factors, and walking/working surface in mind.

column168: On 1/28/20 at approximately 09:45, BNSF Pasco carmen reported that a strong odor was present near the TAMX 2026.  The area was isolated and notifications were made.  Hazmat responders inspected the car and found that all 3 closure plugs were loose on the valves (2 liquid, 1 vapor) within the protective housing.  The vapor valve was identified as being opened just slightly which was contributing to the release.  Air monitoring was established around the car.  Responders removed all three plugs, applied teflon tape to the threads and tool tightened them into the valves.  The odor and air monitoring confirmed that the repair was successful.  Once successful workplace air monitoring was done, workers were allowed to continue working in the area.  Released product dissipated to atmosphere, no cleanup was necessary.
column169: BNSF followed up with Multistar Industries to explain the release.  Multistar should look at their procedures to ensure that tank cars are properly secured prior to transport.  Additionally, new teflon tape should be applied to threads on plugs.(NAR:136)

Driver was unloading when one of his hoses ruptured.  Approximately 50-60 gallons sprayed out (covering him as well) before he could get everything shut down as what was in the customers line was back-flowing out.  The driver needed extra hose for his delivery so he went and picked up another section from our operating center that morning that appeared to be new (inspection sticker supported that).  There ended up being lining damage to the hose from the tank washers putting the wand up in the hose to clean it out.  This is something we have conversations with our network of tank washes.  Being that the hose wasn't his we don't have definitive knowledge which tank wash caused the damage.  He had on his nomex suit, gloves, hard hat with face shield, goggles.  He jumped in the safety shower and cleaned it off.  Driver felt fine  and followed up with him the next day to verify he was still OK.
column169: We have weekly calls with all tankwashes and this incident was brought up with the reminders not to put cleaning wands inside hoses.

Cargo tank was being loaded via a compressor through a 1 inch vapor line attached to the liquid internal valve to allow the gas to bubble up thru the liquefied ammonia in the cargo tank. The operation was being conducted and attended by Hill Brothers Chemical Co. The operation was the evacuation of an anhydrous ammonia refrigeration unit in order to perform maintenance on the system. At the time of the evacuation operation it was unknown if the material would be stored on-site or transported off-site while the system was being worked on. No shipping papers were created at the time of the incident. Chemical Transfer Co's driver was not in charge of the actual loading operation as this operation was under Hill Brothers Chemical Co's personnel control.  After approximately 5 hours of operation the discharge hose from the compressor catastrophically failed at the hose end fitting. Initial thoughts are that the compressor was operated too long and overheated the hose at the fitting and caused the failure. Once the hose failed, the ammonia was released into the surrounding area both from the compressor discharge and through the cargo tank internal valve. General procedures are to have the internal valve closed and used as a check valve. Since Chemical Transfer was not conducting the loading operation we are not sure why the liquid internal was in the open position. As soon as the hose ruptured, the driver turned of the PTO and shut down the truck engine and exited the truck cab.  Once the cloud had moved away from the rear of the cargo tank, Chemical Transfer Co's driver was able to trip the rear remote which closed the internal valves. Vapor hose was hydro tested to 525 psi in Oct 2019, Hose removal date imprinted by Parker Hannifin on rubber 1-1-2022. Hose model is 1 inch 7262, max operating temp 180 def F, WP 350 PSI, NH3 service.
column169: Rewrite all operational procedures. Install secondary check valve in the inline with the liquid internal valve. Utilize stainless steel braided hose from compressor to the delivery line with much higher allowable maximum operating temperature.  Install temperature gauge on compressor discharge outlet to monitor discharge gas temperature. Limit compressor operating time and allow cool down as required to ensure temperature do not reach maximum operating temperatures of hoses.  Still waiting for reports from California Energy Commission, Blythe Fire, Hill Brothers Chemical Co, Parker Hannifin and others at the scene to rewrite all operational procedures.

On January 30, 2020, at approximately 6:40 a.m. CST, facility personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers (RLC) location discovered four (4) 1-pound plastic jugs containing UN1760 corrosive liquid (containing potassium hydroxide) that was damaged during transit as the result of too much weight placed on the cargo. Due to the damage, approximately 48.4 pounds of product released to the trailer interior and palletized cardboard box. At approximately 7:03 a.m. CST, a representative from RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C. (CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Emergency Remediation Specialists(ERS) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. ERS personnel arrived onsite. Following a site assessment, ERS observed approximately 48.4 pounds of UN1760 corrosive liquid (containing potassium hydroxide) released from four (4) 1-gallon plastic jugs to the trailer interior. ERS deployed granular absorbents and citric acid to the impacted trailer interior and worked them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and solution was collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. The impacted cardboard box was then collected and added to the drum for disposal. ERS secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 AM, AFTER FACILITY OPERATIONS START-UP, THE RAILCAR OPERATOR BEGAN TO OFF LOAD A SODIUM HYDROXIDE RAILCAR FROM THE FACILITY PRIVATING SIDING UNLOADING STATION. WHILE PERFORMING ATTENDANCE DUTIES, THE RAILCAR OPERATOR VISUALLY OBSERVED A DRIP COMING FROM THE PRODUCT RAILCAR TRANSFER HOSE CONNECTION, WHICH SENDS PRODUCT TO THE PERMANENT PLANT PIPING SYSTEM. THE RAILCAR OPERATOR LOWERED THE PRESSURE ON THE  PRODUCT HOSE FROM 60 PSI TO 50 PSI, WHICH STOPPED THE DRIP. UPON VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE CONNECTION AND HOSE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FAILURE CAME FROM THE 2" EPDM GASKET AS A RESULT OF WEAR AND TEAR. THE RAILCAR OPERATOR NOTICED THE SIDES OF THE RAILCAR HAD SOME SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE. THE RAILCAR OPERATOR PROCEEDED TO WASH DOWN THE SIDES OF THE RAILCAR WITH WATER. THE WATER, IN TURN, SPRAYED THE PRODUCT DOWN THE SIDE OF THE RAILCAR INSTEAD OF REMOVING THE RESIDUE FULLY.
column169: 1. THE RAILCAR OPERATOR SHOULD HAVE USED A NEUTRALIZER ON THE RESIDUE, AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO MANAGEMENT. THIS WOULD HAVE ENSURED THE PROPER STEPS WOULD HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO PROPERLY REMOVE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESIDUE PRIOR TO SHIPMENT. RAILCAR OPERATOR RETRAINING ON PROPER REPORTING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASES, AND POSSIBLE DISCIPINARY ACTION FOR FAILURE TO REPORT. 2. A MEMBER OF MANAGEMENT FAILED TO PROPERLY INSPECT THE RAILCAR PRIOR TO ITS RELEASE AS REQUIRED BY COMPANY POLICY. IF INSPECTED PROPERLY, THE STAINS WOULD HAVE BEEN DISCOVERED. MANAGEMENT WILL BE RE-TRAINED ON HOW TO PROPERLY INSPECT A RAILCAR FOR ITS RELEASE AND FURTHER ACTION TAKEN TO ENSURE COMPANY POLICY IS PROPERLY IMPLEMENTED. 3. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS AT A NAPA STORE DELIVERING AND PICKING UP SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES (SLABS). WHEN THEY WERE LOADING THE TRAILER WITH THE SLABS THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE ONE PALLET OF SLABS WAS SMOKING. THE DRIVER INFORMED THE NAPA EMPLOYEE TO TAKE THE SMOKING PALLET OF SLABS  OFF HIS TRAILER AND THEY WILL NEED TO TEAR DOWN THE PALLET AND RE-PACKAGE. THE DIVER HELPED TEAR DOWN THE PALLET AND RESTACKED THE SLABS ON A NEW PALLET WITH NEW CARDBOARD IN-BETWEEN THE LAYERS TO MEET THE BCI STACKING AND WRAPPING STANDARDS FOR LEAD ACID BATTERIES.  WHEN OUR DRIVER WAS HELPING TO TEAR DOWN THE SMOLDERING PALLET OF BATTERIES HE NOTICED THAT THE SIDE TERMINALS ON THE BATTERIES HAD PUNCHED THROUGH THE WAFFLE BOARD CAUSING THE BATTERIES TO SHORT CIRCUIT AND THE WAFFLE BOARD TO SMOLDER. AFTER THE SMOLDERING PALLET WAS RE-PACKAGED IT WAS LOADED BACK ONTO THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER INDICATED HERE WAS NO SMELL OF SMOKE FROM THIS PALLET OR ANY OTHER PALLET ON HIS TRAILER.  AS OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING TO HIS NEXT DESTINATION A FEW BLOCKS DOWN THE ROAD, A MOTORIST FLAGGED HIM DOWN AND SAID THERE WAS SMOKE COMING FROM HIS TRAILER. HE PULLED OVER TO CHECK HIS LOAD. HE OPENED THE BACK DOOR OF THE TRAILER AND WENT IN TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE BUT WAS UNABLE TA DO SO. HE NOTED THAT THE 2 PALLETS OF SLABS THAT HE JUST PICKED UP WERE ON FIRE. HE WAS ABLE TO REMOVE HIS PALLET JACK FROM THE TRAILER. HE UNHOOKED HIS TRUCK FROM THE TRAILER AND CALLED 911.  THE LOCAL FIRE COMPANY ARRIVED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. THEY PUT DIKES DOWN TO CONTAIN THE RUN OFF FROM GOING INTO ANY STORM DRAINS. A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CLEAN-UP CREW WAS ALSO CONTACTED TO MITIGATE THE CLEAN UP.

column168: ON JANUARY 16, 2020 A FUEL OIL DELIVERY TRUCK COLLIDED WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 963 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL TO PAVEMENT AND THE SHOULDER OF SALEM ROAD. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY 40 FEET EAST OF THE INTERSECTION OF GRAY STREET AND SALEM ROAD. THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVEMENT, THOUGH SOME OIL MIGRATED TO THE NORTH AND SOUTH ROADWAY SHOULDER. THE BILLERICA FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON-SITE AND DEPLOYED SAND AND ABSORBENT BERMS. MASSDEP ARRIVED ON-SITE AND COORDINATED RESPONSE ACTIONS. A VACUUM TRUCK RECOVERED 640 GALLONS OF OIL WHICH HAD POOLED ON THE PAVEMENT AND WITHIN THE DEPLOYED BERMS. THE GUZZLER VACUUM TRUCKS EXCAVATED THE TOP 6" OF SOIL ALONG THE IMPACTED NORTH AND SOUTH SHOULDER. ADDITIONAL SOIL WAS EXCAVATED FROM ALONG THE IMPACTED NORTH AND SOUTH ROADWAY SHOULDER ON JANUARY 23. 24. AND 27, 2020. SOIL SAMPLES OF THE EXTENT OF EXCAVATION WERE COLLECTED  FOR EXTRACTABLE PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS (EPH) AND VOLATILE PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS (VPH) ALL ANALYTICAL/RESULTS WERE BELOW THE APPLICABLE REPORTABLE CONDITIONS.

column168: ON JANUARY 15, 2020 AT APPROXIMATELY 7 A.M., ONE OF OUR TRUCKS CAUGHT ON FIRE AND IT SPREAD TO THE TANKER IN CLOSE PROXIMITY THAT RUPTURED DUE TO THE FIRE RESULTING IN 7,000 GALLONS OF USED OIL WHICH WAS RELEASED ON OUR YARD LOCATED  IN BACK OF OUR PROPERTY AT 8470 N.W. 68TH STREET, MIAMI, FLORIDA. OTHER VEHICLES  WERE ALSO AFFECTED. OUR EMPLOYEES USED OUR FIRE EXTINGUISHERS TO CONTROL THE FIRE, BUT WERE UNSUCCESSFUL. EVERYONE EVACUATED AND WE CONTACTED 911, OUR NEIGHBORS, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, DERM AND FDEP.  BEFORE IT WAS CLEARED TO RETURN THE FACILITY, A FIRE CAPTAIN ACCOMPANIED OUR SUPERVISOR INTO THE FACILITY TO HAVE OUR SUPERVISOR PLACE TEMPORARY BARRIER COVERS (MAGNETS) ON TOP OF OUR FACILITY DRAINS. AFTER THE CLEARANCE, WE IMMEDIATELY PROCEEDED TO DO THE CLEAN UP BY MEANS OF VACUUM TRUCKS AND PUMP TRUCKS. WE CONTINUED TO PUMP OUT AND PRESSURE CLEAN & DEGREASE EVERY AFFECTED AREA. WE CONTAINED USING BOOMS & DRAIN MAGNETS.  PACKAGE FAILURE; TANK RUPTURE DUE TO FIRE SPILLING 7,000 GALLONS.
column169: Adjusting our procedure to give our trucks more ventilation while loading & offloading as well as mounting a permanent LEL gas monitor in the area.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE (CARGO TANK) FAILURE RELATED TO THIS SPILL.  THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING TWO TANK COMPARTMENTS SIMULTANEOUSLY INTO A SINGLE UNDERGROUND TANK. ONE COMPARTMENT (A) EMPTIED WHILE THE SECOND COMPARTMENT (B) WAS STILL FLOWING PRODUCT. THE DRIVER VIOLATED OUR SOP FOR SAFE LOADING AND UNLOADING. HE REMOVED THE HOSE FROM THE FIRST COMPARTMENT (A) TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK WITHOUT SHUTTING OFF FLOW FROM COMPARTMENT (B). WHEN THE HOSE FROM COMPARTMENT (A) FROM THE RECEIVING TANK THE BACK PRESSURE DUE TO THE CONTINUING DELIVERY FROM THE COMPARTMENT (B) RESULTED IN A SPILL, ESTIMATED TO BE 10-15 GALLONS. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE PAVEMENT AND WAS CLEANED UP.
column169: THE DRIVER WILL RETRAINING IN OUR SOP FOR SAFE LOADING AND UNLOADING.

column168: On the morning of 17 January 2020, trailer 235A, an MC331 tanker, was dropped off at the Grammer Logistics shop located at 1528 New Stanton – Ruffs Dale Road, Ruffs Dale Pennsylvania to have two brass grounding studs installed on the passenger side plumbing cage.  Driver Kimber Runyan dropped the unit off, discussed with the shop staff the installation requested and departed for the Ryder Repair shop in New Stanton to have a few minor repairs done.  A short while later he returned to the New Stanton shop to wait on the units to be completed.   At a point near noon, Driver Sean Randolph, an owner-operator leased to Grammer Logistics, 804-852-6005, dropped his trailer 877, also an MC331 tanker, for routine preventative maintenance.   As part of the routine maintenance procedure, a test is performed to check to see if there is pressure behind each dust cap at every hose connection point.  Trailer 235A failed this test.    As Mr. Runyan’s tractor repairs had been completed, he returned to pick it up.  After a short time, he returned to the Grammer Logistics repair shop. He was informed that his trailer had failed the leak test.  He hooked to it and re-parked it on the “back pad” at the rear of the shop, just to the left of the garage door.  He uncoupled and drove around to the front of the building.  He then went into the office and conversed with mechanic Ms. Jessica Noga.     Mechanic Mr. Andrew DeAngelo, a nine-year veteran employee here was on the back pad starting the “vent out” procedure necessary to relieve any pressure and vapors inside unit 235A.  This procedure requires opening valves and attaching a blower to blow normal air through the trailer.  It is unclear to myself and others as to the possible amount of butane vapors present at the ground level.  These vapors found an ignition source.  It is unknown exactly where Mr. Shawn Wilson was at this point but it is believed he was close to Mr. DeAngelo, as he would have been learning about this procedure as a newly hired technician.    First Fire Event   Inside the office, Mr. Runyan heard the rumble and felt the blast.  He pushed Ms. Noga to the office floor then the two ran out of the building **** (I do not know what door they left through)   As they were on their way to the Emergency Evacuation Rally point, Mr. Runyan saw Mr. DeAngelo engulfed in flames.  Mr. Runyan sprinted to his aid and put the flames out on Mr. DeAngelo’s clothing.  Mr. Wilson was also injured but managed to get a call for assistance to Westmoreland County’s Emergency Response Center.  Within minutes the first responding units arrived from Mutual Aid.    Second Fire Event    As Mutual Aid was assessing and treating the burn victims a second explosion occurred.  The source was not readily evident but footage from a news helicopter clearly shows a column of fire, well in excess of 30’, exiting the roof above bay #1 of the shop.   Mr. DeAngelo and Mr. Wilson were transported to UPMC Mercy, in Pittsburgh, via helicopter.
column169: Grammer Logistics has improved operating procedures to prevent a recurrence.

column168: A vehicle tanker containing 4,800 gallons of sodium hypochlorite was parked with the tractor removed from underneath the tanker in a paved parking lot during in transit storage. The tanker was located on an uneven sloped asphalt surface that was unable to support the weight of the full tanker resulting in the asphalt to give way under the right landing gear and causing the tanker to tip over onto its side. Once the tanker rolled over, the dome cover lidlhad not been fully secured and product begin to leak out of the dome cover. Upon discovery of the rolled over tanker, Hasa responding employees immediately begin to mitigate the spill. The responders were able to capture the product Ieaking from the tanker int6 secondary containment containers and transferring product to 53 gallon drums. The responders noticed product was Ieaking directly from the dome, which was not fully closed. The dome cover lid bolts were tightened and no further product leaked from the dome. The tanker with the remaining product was lifted and uprighted with the assistance of two heavy duty tow trucks and secured with a tractor underneath the tanker. An inspection of the tanker was performed and there was no visible damage or leaks from the tanker and or the dome. Approximately 380 gallons were released from the tanker, with 330 gallons captured in secondary containment by responding employees. Thus, 50 gallons were released to soil which was recovered by third a party hazmat response company.

column168: MY NAME IS JAMES ROACH, I OWN LEGEND TRANSPORT AND STORAGE. I LEASE PARKING SPACES FOR TRUCKS AT MY YARD LOCATED AT 7626 LEOPARD ST. CORPUS CHRISTI, TX 78409. ON 1/21/2020. A PIPELINE CREW WORKING ON INSTALLATION OF A NEW PIPELINE BEHIND MY PROPERTY INFORMED ME THAT THEY HAD ENCOUNTERED A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF OIL POOLED ON THE GROUND JUST BEHIND MY PROPERTY.  I MET THEM TO SURVEY AND CONCURRED THAT THE OIL HAD COME FROM MY PROPERTY AS EVIDENCED IN FOLLOWING THE TRAIL BACK TO THE POINT OF RELEASE , WHICH WAS ON MY PROPERTY. A RENTER WHO IS AN OWNER OPERATOR LEASED TO TROUT TRUCKING COMPANY THAT PARKS IN THE SPOT WHERE THE RELEASE OCCURED WAS SUSPECTED AS THE CULPRIT. I NOTIFIED TROUT TRUCKING AND THEY SENT DAVID BARRERA AND ART GARCIA TO INVESTIGATE. THEY LOOKED AT THE SPILL AND DECIDED IT WAS NOT A PRODUCT FROM THEIR TRAILER , BUT THAT IT WAS USED MOTOR OIL . I SENT A SAMPLE FOR TESTING AND THE FINDINGS ARE THAT IT IS IN FACT VGO. A PRODUCT THAT THEY HAUL FREQUENTLY . I HAVE ALSO BEEN CONTACTED BY A WITNESS WHO SAID THAT IT WAS CONFESSED TO HIM THAT THE SUSPECT ADMITTED TO THE INTENTIONAL RELEASE BECAUSE HE DIDNT FULLY UNLOAD ALL DELIVERY.
column169: TROUT TRUCKING IS REFUSING TO INVESTIGATE FURTHER OR TO REVIEW THE EVIDENCE PROVING THIS IS THEIR LIABILITY. I AM BURDENED WITH THE CLEAN UP . THEIR STANCE ON THIS ISSUE IS AN INDICATOR OF HOW THEY WILL LIKELY REACT TO ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS OR MAYBE EVEN PAST INCIDENTS.

column168: As the driver was filling the third compartment on the transport trailer, an error alarm went off and the driver was unclear about what the error was for. The alarm was in response to the truck overfilling. The overfill resulted in product entering the vapor recovery line. The driver removed the vapor line and 20 gallons of product escaped rapidly.
column169: Completed internal review of incident. Educated the driver on what the error messages refer to. Continue to give operators the tools needed to clean up spills effectively and efficiently. Inspect all sensors and parts that should prevent overfilling.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: While loading crude oil for transport the driver opened the valve and did not get the valve closed completely causing the truck to overfill and 4 bbls of crude oil to spill.
column169: Completed internal review of incident. Review loading process and how to properly close the truck valve. Emphasize importance of monitoring the loading process. Driver was assigned to safety training courses.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: The driver was loading Crude oil when he heard a pop from the hose between the pump and the tank on the truck. The loading hose cracked.  As a result of this incident approximately 1 barrel was lost to the ground. There were no injuries or vehicles towed as a result of this incident.
column169: The loading hose was removed from service. After an internal investigation, the driver was retrained on pre-trip inspections of equipment.

column168: Driver states that he properly identified UNL 1 vs. UNL 2 by sticking the tanks and comparing levels to Veeder-Root printout information.  After delivering premium unleaded, driver began to unload regular unleaded into UNL 1 (10k nominal).  Driver observed that tank seemed to be building pressure and product was backing up in spill bucket.  Driver stopped unloading into UNL 1 and began dropping into UNL 2.  Driver finished unloading compartment into UNL 2 and went to next compartment.  Driver overlooked that UNL 2 was 6k (nominal).  As second compartment finished unloading the overfill alarm went off.   Driver hooked back to UNL 1 to finish unloading trailer.  As driver was unloading into UNL 1 he noticed that product was spilling out of UNL 2 onto the surrounding concrete.  Driver stopped the unloading process and set out absorbent pads. The store called the Fire Department, which came out and set out some more absorbent pads and then left the scene. It is estimated approximately 20 gallons of product spilled from the tank.
column169: Coach this driver specifically, and all drivers during next terminal safety meetings, to get help immediately any time a delivery irregularity develops.  In this case, as soon as the driver detected pressure build-up in tank 1 he should have called for direction.  Options such as getting a senior driver involved, diverting the load to a different location, or asking customer for maintenance support can be managed once the call is made.  Have vapor recovery system inspected for proper operation.  Initial pressure build-up may have been due to ice build up or maintenance issue.  Consider properly capping the open vapor tube OR consider opening all gasoline tanks with proper vapor recovery.  Physically label the regular unleaded tanks appropriately to identify tanks relative to Veeder-Root and tank size.
